article.description: Indiana Fever rookie Tamika Catchings got a rare view of the action from the bench, then took over when she got back in the game.
article.headline: Catchings takes charge in second half, completes rally
article.linkText: Catchings takes charge in second half, completes Fever rally
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Indiana Fever rookie Tamika Catchings got a rare view of the action from the bench, then took over when she got back in the game.

Catchings and her teammates struggled early, so Indiana coach Nell Fortner decided to give the WNBA's second-leading scorer a break as Sacramento led 27-13 with 6:39 left in the first half.

The rookie watched her team fall behind 31-15 before reserve Rita Williams scored nine quick points to cut Indiana's deficit to 31-26 at the half.

In the second half, Catchings went to work, scoring with 15 of her 21 points and grabbing nine of her 12 rebounds to lead Indiana to a 67-60 victory over the Monarchs.

Catchings also set a club record with five 3-pointers.

Fortner said she didn't pull Catchings because of her play.

"Catchings is a great player. There's no question about that. Sometimes we have a tendency to watch her play. We've got some other good players on this team, and they need to know they can play,'' Fortner said.

The Indiana rookie came into the game averaging 18.3 points and 8.8 rebounds while playing an average of 37.5 minutes per game. She played 35 minutes Friday.

"We came out in the second half after talking about defense. We
focused on that,'' Catchings said.

She shot 2-of-6 from the field in the first half. In the second
half, she was 5-of-8, and hit all four of her 3-point attempts.

"The first half they were keying on me so much and I was
getting open shots,'' Catchings said. "The group that went in when
I was out, they did a great job.''

Frigid shooting by the Fever in the first half helped the
Monarchs take a 31-15 lead with 4:30 to go in the period.

Indiana shot just 6-of-28 (21 percent) until that point. But the
Monarchs, who started by hitting 13 of 24 shots, missed their next
five attempts and had three turnovers. Williams scored nine of
Indiana's next 11 points to cut the lead to five at the break. She
finished with a season-high 13 points.

"She was amazing,'' Catchings said. "She's able to be a point
guard, and that's what we need.''

The loss was the fifth in a row for the Monarchs (2-11), who got
24 points from Tangela Smith.

Nikki McCray added 16 points for Indiana (6-7), while reserve
Lady Grooms had 14 for the Monarchs.

Catchings recorded her fifth double-double of the season.

The Fever had just seven turnovers, leading to only six points for Sacramento. The Monarchs had 14 turnovers, which led to 16 points by Indiana.
